**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
(I'm not sure this is a request, maybe I've juste missed something in the doc, I'm sorry if this is the case but I've looked everywhere and I can't get it to work)

I'm trying to perform an inference in C++ with both input and output already on the device (as an intermediary step in a process for example). I'm using DirectML as provider, and I've seen that creating DML memory is supported since 1.10, but I can't get the session to run properly.

**System information**
- ONNX Runtime version (you are using): 1.10 version (nuget in C++ project)

**Describe the solution you'd like**
I'd like the session to run normally and set the value passed as output to the output of the model, without copy to the CPU.

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
I've considered getting the data on the CPU and transfer them back to the device, but it adds an overhead.

**Additional context**
Here is the code I use with this [model.onnx](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/7864780/model.txt) (it's just a Pytorch 4x upsample exported with opset 11) for testing. Everything runs fine until the ``session.Run`` call, where the program just stops.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include "onnxruntime_cxx_api.h"
#include "dml_provider_factory.h"

int main(int argc, char** argv) {

    const std::string model_s = "model.onnx";
    std::basic_string<ORTCHAR_T> model = std::basic_string<ORTCHAR_T>(model_s.begin(), model_s.end());
    
    // onnxruntime setup
    Ort::Env env(ORT_LOGGING_LEVEL_WARNING, "batch-model-explorer");
    Ort::SessionOptions session_options;
    OrtSessionOptionsAppendExecutionProvider_DML(session_options, 0);
    Ort::Session session = Ort::Session(env, model.c_str(), session_options);

    Ort::IoBinding io_binding = Ort::IoBinding::IoBinding(session);
    Ort::MemoryInfo memory_info("DML", OrtAllocatorType::OrtDeviceAllocator, 0, OrtMemType::OrtMemTypeDefault);
    Ort::RunOptions run_options;

    // Create input tensor with 0 on device memory
    std::vector<int64_t> input_shape{ 1,3,1000,1000 };
    std::vector<float> input_tensor_values(1*3*1000*1000, 0.0f);
    Ort::Value input_tensor = Ort::Value::CreateTensor<float>(memory_info, input_tensor_values.data(), input_tensor_values.size(), input_shape.data(), 4);
    // bind the tensor to the input of the model
    io_binding.BindInput("input", input_tensor);

    // Create output tensor on device memory
    std::vector<int64_t> output_shape{ 1,3,4*1000,4*1000 };
    std::vector<float> output_tensor_values(1*3*4000*4000, 0.0f);
    Ort::Value output_tensor = Ort::Value::CreateTensor<float>(memory_info, output_tensor_values.data(), output_tensor_values.size(), output_shape.data(), 4);
    // bind the tensor to the output of the model
    io_binding.BindOutput("output", output_tensor);
    
    try {
        session.Run(run_options, io_binding);
    }
    catch (const Ort::Exception& exception)
    {
        std::cout << "ERROR running model inference: " << exception.what() << std::endl;
        return -1;
    }
    catch (const std::exception& exception)
    {
        std::cout << "ERROR running model inference: " << exception.what() << std::endl;
        return -1;
    }

    std::cout << "Done!" << std::endl;

    return 0;
}

```

Thanks for any help on this!
